    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1081609994" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1081609994" />
    <a title="Czarny Pies" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/29160274-czarny-pies"><img alt="Czarny Pies" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1400687408p2/29160274.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1081609994?book_show_action=true">Oct 16, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Czarny Pies" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Czarny Pies" href="/user/show/29160274-czarny-pies">Czarny Pies</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">English and French Canadians</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Czarny by: </span>
      I have been a Richler fan for over 30 years.
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29160274-czarny-pies?shelf=canadian-literature">canadian-literature</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1081609994" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11816473205820756824">Mordecai Richler&apos;s novels constitutea national treasure. He belonged to the Jewish community of Montreal which is city divided between English and French speakers. Mordecai Richler spent his career mercilessly lampooning the follies of all three groups. Richler certainly always kept me laughing but I am so close to his concerns I am not quite sure what the nature of his appeal is outside of Canada. <br/><br/>Barney&apos;s Version contains an eloquent statement of the dominant points of Richler&apos;s literary opus </span>
  <span id="freeText11816473205820756824" style="display:none">Mordecai Richler's novels constitutea national treasure. He belonged to the Jewish community of Montreal which is city divided between English and French speakers. Mordecai Richler spent his career mercilessly lampooning the follies of all three groups. Richler certainly always kept me laughing but I am so close to his concerns I am not quite sure what the nature of his appeal is outside of Canada. <br /><br />Barney's Version contains an eloquent statement of the dominant points of Richler's literary opus which are:<br /><br />-1- the need to nurture Canadian literature should never be used as an excuse for inferior writing<br />-2- the need to protect the French language in Canada does not justify discrimination against English speakers in the province of Quebec<br />-3- there is no need to resort to kitsch in order to promote one's pride in being Jewish<br />-4- to live together successfully Canadians must start by loving and respecting one another on individual level<br /><br />Barney's Version is a delightful novel. Barney is a glorious curmudgeon who lives in awe of writers and artists which leads him to devote his entrepreneurial skills to promote literature and culture. In turn, he is treated as a vulgar money-grubber by the very people he so greatly admires. He is proud of being Jewish but is ultimately more interested in the ups and downs of the Montreal Canadians than he is in the fate of the state of Israel. He is rejected by the woman he loves but finds himself being the beneficiary of great love from sources that he never expected.<br /><br />Barney's Version is one of Richler's most glorious achievements. All Canadian book lovers should read it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11816473205820756824" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


