<div id="review_239031787" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/239031787" />
    <a title="R." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/184928-r"><img alt="R." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1509742903p2/184928.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/239031787?book_show_action=true">Nov 23, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="R." class="user" itemprop="url" name="R." href="/user/show/184928-r">R.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780307476883" href="/book/show/7669528-barney-s-version">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/184928-r?shelf=2011">2011</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer239031787" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1200742761321667433"><i>Barney&apos;s Version</i> is Richler&apos;s Giller Prize winning version of Saul Bellow&apos;s National Book Award winning classic, <i>Herzog</i>. <br/><br/>A good, at times better, Canadian cover version of an American favorite. So you think Kids in the Hall and Saturday Night Live. So you think Barenaked Ladies and, I dunno, <i>Creed</i>. Yes. Fine. <i>Fine</i>. So be it. <br/><br/>It&apos;s about Barney Panofsky. Panofsky, a man with, oy, troubles of his <i>own</i>, let me tell you, sonny, but does he let that get him down? No. No, he doesn&apos;t let that get him dow</span>
  <span id="freeText1200742761321667433" style="display:none"><i>Barney's Version</i> is Richler's Giller Prize winning version of Saul Bellow's National Book Award winning classic, <i>Herzog</i>. <br /><br />A good, at times better, Canadian cover version of an American favorite. So you think Kids in the Hall and Saturday Night Live. So you think Barenaked Ladies and, I dunno, <i>Creed</i>. Yes. Fine. <i>Fine</i>. So be it. <br /><br />It's about Barney Panofsky. Panofsky, a man with, oy, troubles of his <i>own</i>, let me tell you, sonny, but does he let that get him down? No. No, he doesn't let that get him down.<br /><br />No way. And let me tell you why. He vents. He gets it out. He gets it down in writing. <br /><br />He...he writes letters. And <i>what letters</i> he writes. And unlike Moses Herzog, they aren't in his head, these letters. No philatelic flights of imagination, these. No. They're sent. Par avion. <i>Sign here, please.</i> Or they're (and this is keeping with the times in which said book was written) faxed. <br /><br />What do they do, these letters? What's the upshot? They...hmmmm. Hold on a minute. Lemme dig around for the right...the right...the right <i>mot juste</i>.<br /><br />The letters, they...well, they <i>arrive</i>. <br /><br />Note: Something to take away from the novel is that you leave life guilty. Caught dead to rights on a lot of things. Sure. <i>Throw the book at me</i>. And who doesn't? Who wouldn't want to? To have a black mark or two? It's flavor. Still, it's the big crimes...of which I might add we're totally innocent, right?...It's the big crimes we're never around, never <i>all there</i> when people finally see it our way. We're either taking a nap in the dirt or drooling pudding down our shirt. </span>
  <a data-text-id="1200742761321667433" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


