  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_39298724" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/39298724" />
    <a title="Matt" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/66632-matt"><img alt="Matt" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1178675796p2/66632.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/39298724?book_show_action=true">Dec 04, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Matt" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Matt" href="/user/show/66632-matt">Matt</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780671028466" href="/book/show/766085.Barney_s_Version">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer39298724" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1630158017839127865">Most of <u>Barney&apos;s Version</u> is structured as an autobiography of a bitter old curmudgeon. Barney, the titular protagonist, is trying to proclaim his innocence - both of the crime of murdering his friend Boogie (for which he had been acquitted, by the law) and of the more general charge of being a bastard and a sycophant. He totally fails at the latter - in fact, Barney is so uncharitable, so grating, that (his humor notwithstanding) the reader begins to tire of his voice by the end of the book.<br/><br/>All </span>
  <span id="freeText1630158017839127865" style="display:none">Most of <u>Barney's Version</u> is structured as an autobiography of a bitter old curmudgeon. Barney, the titular protagonist, is trying to proclaim his innocence - both of the crime of murdering his friend Boogie (for which he had been acquitted, by the law) and of the more general charge of being a bastard and a sycophant. He totally fails at the latter - in fact, Barney is so uncharitable, so grating, that (his humor notwithstanding) the reader begins to tire of his voice by the end of the book.<br /><br />All of this is redeemed, however, in the final chapter. The miraculous twist of the book is not the revelation of the truth of Boogie's death (either it could turn out that Boogie had been alive and hiding for the past 30 years, or it could turn out that Barney had in fact murdered his best friend - neither would have been particularly surprising). No, the surprise at the end of the book is the sudden pain - the real heartache - that bubbles out in the last chapter. Barney's character had used his bitterness and sarcasm to keep any real emotion at bay - the sudden bearing of heart at the end of the book shows the effect such callousness has on everyone he touches.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1630158017839127865" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

