    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2038304111" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2038304111" />
    <a title="Aliki Bitsakakis" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/37291079-aliki-bitsakakis"><img alt="Aliki Bitsakakis" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1432503982p2/37291079.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2038304111?book_show_action=true">Jul 27, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Aliki Bitsakakis" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Aliki Bitsakakis" href="/user/show/37291079-aliki-bitsakakis">Aliki Bitsakakis</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/37291079-aliki-bitsakakis?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2038304111" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8949803352774961389">Organized chaos. That is the only way I can think to accurately describe the genius behind this piece of writing. Upon opening Barney’s Version by Mordecai Richler, the reader is transported to the scattered mind of Barney Panofsky, an old man sadistically reflecting on his intricate life. We are introduced to stories surrounding his three wives, the one love of his life, his ungrateful children, frustrating business, arch-rival, and most importantly, the so-called murder of his best friend, of </span>
  <span id="freeText8949803352774961389" style="display:none">Organized chaos. That is the only way I can think to accurately describe the genius behind this piece of writing. Upon opening Barney’s Version by Mordecai Richler, the reader is transported to the scattered mind of Barney Panofsky, an old man sadistically reflecting on his intricate life. We are introduced to stories surrounding his three wives, the one love of his life, his ungrateful children, frustrating business, arch-rival, and most importantly, the so-called murder of his best friend, of which Barney has been accused. However, this novel is not brilliant due to its plot lines or characters; it is the way in which it is all written that had me unable to put it down. <br /><br />Imagine you’re telling a story to a friend. Your mind tends to get side tracked, and your story becomes enveloped in these branches, where you go on to explain meaningless details and things that you were reminded of as you were telling your story. You may focus too heavily on what someone was wearing and you persistently wind back to a specific thought, of how that one person managed to get away from you. You avoid certain details, trying to cover up particular events; no matter how much someone pries, prompting them to think you are hiding something. That is precisely how Barney’s Version is written, and it is quite miraculous. Richler has managed to capture the human mind in his writing, complete with lapses of memory—due to Barney’s withering age—inaccuracies in bits of trivia—corrected by his eldest son in the footnotes—and the almost tiring jumping between plots and time periods. I found it difficult to get into this book at first because of this structure, but once I got into the flow, I was fully immersed in the life of Barney Panofsky. I recognized that this is how all of our minds work, even if we have never realized it before. Barney is a troubled man and he tells troubling stories. He may begin to tell us about his first wife, Clara, and her horrendous drawings, then be reminded of a funny story his friend Boogie had once said, jumping to tell us about what he was currently doing in the kitchen of his apartment, then name the Seven Dwarfs as a memory aid, complain about politics in Quebec, go on to tell us about his son Saul and the antics he was up to, then muse about his last wife Miriam, and finally going back to tell us how Clara’s story came to an end. It was only when you were deep into it, that things were beginning to be revealed, and then it becomes apparent why Barney has been beating around the bush so much. None of his marriages ended well. He was constantly drunk and making those around him uncomfortable. Even from a young age, he was a bitter old man in search of something resembling a fulfilled life. Even though, as a reader, you know that he cannot possibly find this happiness, one continues to hope as the novel progresses. <br /><br />I have previously read The Apprenticeship of Duddy Kravitz, also written by Mordecai Richler, which is what prompted me to pick up this novel as well. I was pleasantly surprised because I found these two novels so similar, increasing my love for Richler, but drastically different at the same time. This sort of organized chaos is completely unique to Barney’s Version. However, the thing that makes me still think about The Apprenticeship of Duddy Kravitz is that I feel as if I actually know Duddy. If someone were to approach me and begin speaking like him and acting in the way I imagine him to act, I would be able to immediately identify a Duddy Kravitz impersonator. Again, this all comes from Richler’s expert writing. He has a knack for each of his characters speaking in such distinct and creative ways that these impressions are engraved in your mind. I did not think I would find a character as particular as Duddy, but Barney has now also made such an impression that I feel as if he is an old friend and I went along with him through all these stories. By the end of the novel, I felt as if I too were a character in his twisted life. Things like repeated phrases, character development through openness of information, and the pure fact that this was a look into someone’s mind, solidified Barney Panofsky as a real person. <br /><br />The best books are those that have the reader thinking for days following its close. When taking Barney’s age and memory lapses into account, you begin to question whether anything you had just witnessed was in fact true. He openly admitted to not revealing certain pieces of information at times, which he would then discuss. But, still, you never know in that chaotic mind of his. And that is what makes this novel all the more interesting. I find myself hungry for more. I could have read an entire series about Barney’s life, written in the same disorganized style. I want to know everything about Terry McIver, Barney’s arch nemesis. I want to read everything Terry has written, criticizing Barney. I am itching to analyze every police report surrounding the murder/disappearance of Boogie. I want to learn about the lives of Barney’s children in depth and the lives of his wives after their encounters with Barney. I want to pick and dissect at Barney’s mind even further. And that is how you can tell that this book is definitely worth reading again and again. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="8949803352774961389" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


