    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_14528561" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/14528561" />
    <a title="Bill" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/810550-bill"><img alt="Bill" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1462234651p2/810550.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/14528561?book_show_action=true">Feb 04, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bill" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bill" href="/user/show/810550-bill">Bill</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/810550-bill?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer14528561" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3600462723050274711">If there is one author who I would drop anything to catch an interview with, it is the acerbic Mordecai Richler. Having grown up English in the working class Jewish sector of Montreal, he has always been a breath of fresh air with his outspoken views, particularly on Quebec separatism.<br/>I have always meant to read him, and Barney&apos;s Version is my first.<br/><br/>This is a fictional testament of a man driven to clear his name after his nemesis, fellow writer Terry McIvor, writes his memoirs, leaving Barney&apos;s </span>
  <span id="freeText3600462723050274711" style="display:none">If there is one author who I would drop anything to catch an interview with, it is the acerbic Mordecai Richler. Having grown up English in the working class Jewish sector of Montreal, he has always been a breath of fresh air with his outspoken views, particularly on Quebec separatism.<br />I have always meant to read him, and Barney's Version is my first.<br /><br />This is a fictional testament of a man driven to clear his name after his nemesis, fellow writer Terry McIvor, writes his memoirs, leaving Barney's legacy a tad smeared. At least to Barney it is.<br />Barney has Richler's voice; so much so that it has been widely speculated that Barney's Version is largely autobiographical. It's not, although Richler has been quoted as saying, "when I wrote the novel I was Barney Panofsky, but not before and not after". <br />Despite the fact that it did meander somewhat, and storywise I found it uninteresting, this is still a fine read, with healthy doses of dry wit.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3600462723050274711" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

